sentences: Clive Blackmore Barda OBE, FRSA (born 14 January 1945) is a London-based, British freelance photographer best known for capturing the performances of classical musicians and artists of the stage (opera, ballet and theatre).
Barda was born in 1945 and spent his early childhood in Alexandria, Egypt, where his father was a lawyer and his mother a painter.

Barda decided to combine his interests in photography and classical music, and a chance encounter with a journalist for South Wales Magazine led to his first commission: photographing the harpist Susan Drake at home, on 12 November 1968.:
In 1969, I went to a concert at London's South Bank, where pianist Daniel Barenboim and the cellist Jacqueline du Pré were playing Beethoven sonatas.
In her review of Barda's book Performance! (2000) for The Guardian, Charlotte Higgins stated:
By 2012, Barda had already produced more than a million photographs,: 6  and has been referred to as the doyen of British music photography.
In 1970, Barda married Rosalind Mary Whiteley; they have three sons.

OBE in the 2016 New Year Honours list, for services to photography.
Honorary fellowship of the Musicians' Company, July 2016.

Over the past 30 years, Barda has photographed anyone who is anyone in music, from late, great luminaries such as Lucia Popp, Olivier Messiaen, Benjamin Britten and Charles Groves to today's young stars such as Evgeny Kissin, David Daniels and Cecilia Bartoli.
During his career spanning over five decades, Barda has created a collection of over a million photographs of performers, composers, and conductors.

The family returned to England in 1956.: 4  Barda attended Bryanston School and graduated from Birkbeck College, University of London (BA Hons Modern Langs), aspiring to apply his knowledge of modern languages as a commodities broker in the City.: 19  His early interest in photography was mostly documentary; while studying for his degree, he travelled to Romania to photograph the painted monasteries of Moldavia.:
20  When he was twenty, following a friend's suggestion, he attended his first concert of classical music: an evening of Viennese music conducted by John Barbirolli.
Soon after, he started attending concerts several times per week, and listening regularly to BBC Radio 3.: 20
21  Within a few months, Barda had his big break:
The rehearsal took place at the Queen Elizabeth Hall the following Tuesday, and Barda showed the resulting contact sheets to Barenboim a few days later, in the Royal Festival Hall's green room.
During the following decades, Barda has portrayed the world's leading classical musicians, as well as performers in opera, dance, theatre and musicals, as a freelance photographer.

The fact that I often spent hours with the artists and was perceived as a member of the recording team fed into my work in a number of ways (...) bolstering my sense of affinity with the musicians and their work.
After a decade as a professional photographer, Barda began to exhibit his work, in the UK and abroad:
